htc550605125.boxmover.common.stage

Class Stage

  • java.lang.Object
    • htc550605125.boxmover.common.stage.StageBase
      • htc550605125.boxmover.common.stage.Stage
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable<Stage>

    public class Stage
extends StageBase
implements java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable<Stage>
     The game stage.
 It only contains the basic control of abstract Element.
 It has an one-dimensional array of ElementSet, and
 here is the implement detail of element management:
      First we have the concept of element(player, wall, box, destination).
      They are defined in Element. Then, every grid of the game
      stage is a ElementSet which contains a set of Element.
      The Stage manages the ElementSets in an one-dimensional array,
      because the Stage could be used without the actually dimension
      information. In other words, the Stage could run with either
      2D-box-moving game or 3D-box-moving game. The trick is in Dim
      and Vector.
    See Also:
    Dim, Vector, Serialized Form
